00:06:20.294 --> 00:06:21.960
But I just want to
give you a background

00:06:21.960 --> 00:06:24.330
so you can have an
understanding of what happened.

00:06:24.330 --> 00:06:30.950
So in 1994, there was a genocide
that took place in Rwanda.

00:06:30.950 --> 00:06:35.950
The population at the time
was about 84% Hutu, about 15%

00:06:35.950 --> 00:06:39.790
Tutsi, and about 1% of
indigenous Twa people.

00:06:39.790 --> 00:06:42.300
And the story goes
that-- the history

00:06:42.300 --> 00:06:46.540
goes that the Belgian
colonial powers helped

00:06:46.540 --> 00:06:51.570
construct these identities--
Hutu, the majority, Tutsi

00:06:51.570 --> 00:06:56.860
the minority, and also
had put Tutsi in power

00:06:56.860 --> 00:07:00.690
as indirect rulers during
Belgian colonization.

00:07:00.690 --> 00:07:03.110
And this created a lot of
conflict between the Hutu

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:04.790
and Tutsi communities.

00:07:04.790 --> 00:07:07.650
And I'm saying communities
because Hutu and Tutsi are not

00:07:07.650 --> 00:07:09.820
exactly ethnic identities.

00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:13.780
In Rwanda, everybody speaks
the same language, Kinyarwanda,

00:07:13.780 --> 00:07:15.670
and had come from
similar backgrounds.

00:07:15.670 --> 00:07:17.990
So these divisions
were not particularly

00:07:17.990 --> 00:07:22.630
salient or meaningful until
the Belgian colonizers

00:07:22.630 --> 00:07:23.670
came to power.

00:07:23.670 --> 00:07:27.310
So again, they favored the
Tutsi, who basically they

00:07:27.310 --> 00:07:31.410
gave a lot of positions to you
in government and in education.

00:07:31.410 --> 00:07:35.040
And after that, the Hutu
extremist government

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:37.680
came to power in the
First and Second Republic

00:07:37.680 --> 00:07:43.750
and started to persecute the
Tutsi population between 1959

00:07:43.750 --> 00:07:45.750
and 1994.

00:07:45.750 --> 00:07:49.830
In 1994, on the 6th of
April, that Hutu hardliner

00:07:49.830 --> 00:07:52.930
president,
Habyarimana, his plane

00:07:52.930 --> 00:07:55.260
was shot down on
the 6th of April.

00:07:55.260 --> 00:07:57.700
And on the 7th, the
Rwandan Armed Forces

00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:01.170
and the Interahamwe Militia
started the systematic killing

00:08:01.170 --> 00:08:04.080
of Tutsi and moderate Hutus.

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:07.190
And as we know, many of us who
were alive during this period

00:08:07.190 --> 00:08:09.800
or who were watching the news,
the international community

00:08:09.800 --> 00:08:11.680
really abandoned Rwanda.

00:08:11.680 --> 00:08:14.380
We've even seen recent articles
come out in "Foreign Policy"

00:08:14.380 --> 00:08:17.410
that heads of state
in the United States

00:08:17.410 --> 00:08:19.530
knew what was going
on and were concerned

00:08:19.530 --> 00:08:22.110
about calling it a genocide
because of what intervention

00:08:22.110 --> 00:08:23.030
would mean.

00:08:23.030 --> 00:08:26.050
And so these debates are
ongoing, but in Rwanda people

00:08:26.050 --> 00:08:28.330
generally feel that
the United Nations

00:08:28.330 --> 00:08:30.980
and international
community let them down.

00:08:30.980 --> 00:08:34.620
So the killings began, and
there were about 100 days

00:08:34.620 --> 00:08:37.049
of genocidal killings all
throughout the country

00:08:37.049 --> 00:08:38.640
with very popular involvement.

00:08:38.640 --> 00:08:42.059
So killings on the ground,
we call it low tech

00:08:42.059 --> 00:08:47.330
killing with machetes and clubs
and other household and farming

00:08:47.330 --> 00:08:48.320
weapons.

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:52.510
And on the 4th of July in
1994, the Rwandan Patriotic

00:08:52.510 --> 00:08:54.850
Front and the Rwandan
Patriotic Army,

00:08:54.850 --> 00:08:59.520
who had been in exile
in Uganda, came in,

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:02.820
took control of the
capital city of Kigali,

00:09:02.820 --> 00:09:05.230
liberated the
country, and started

00:09:05.230 --> 00:09:06.930
to form a transitional
government.

00:09:06.930 --> 00:09:09.540
So that's the history
we've got of what

00:09:09.540 --> 00:09:11.650
happened during the genocide.

00:09:11.650 --> 00:09:15.550
So the current RPF, Rwandan
Patriotic Front-led government

00:09:15.550 --> 00:09:17.390
and the state in
general, has really

00:09:17.390 --> 00:09:20.620
attempted to rebuild social
order and social fabric

00:09:20.620 --> 00:09:23.460
in Rwanda since 1994.

00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:25.960
And the goal of the state
with regard to survivors,

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:29.320
which is specifically
what I research,

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:31.740
is threefold as
identified by the state--

00:09:31.740 --> 00:09:36.610
to provide security, to combat
genocide ideology and denial,

00:09:36.610 --> 00:09:39.590
and to reunite the country
under the Banyarwanda,

00:09:39.590 --> 00:09:43.340
that we are all Rwandan, we
are all one Rwandan people.

00:09:43.340 --> 00:09:45.780
And these ideals
are very prevalent

00:09:45.780 --> 00:09:49.440
and have been there since the
end of the genocide in 1994

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:51.400
and are heavily present
in the reconstruction

00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:54.090
that we see today.

00:09:54.090 --> 00:09:56.560
So just some statistics
about survivors before we

00:09:56.560 --> 00:09:59.577
get into the meat,
the good stuff, where

00:09:59.577 --> 00:10:01.160
we're going to enter
into these spaces

00:10:01.160 --> 00:10:03.570
and I'm going to tell you a
little bit about these themes

00:10:03.570 --> 00:10:05.580
that I've identified
and the stories that

00:10:05.580 --> 00:10:09.060
go with them, the experiences
that I've had being in Rwanda

00:10:09.060 --> 00:10:11.430
and being with different people.

00:10:11.430 --> 00:10:13.910
But we have about 1
million genocide victims,

00:10:13.910 --> 00:10:17.600
Tutsi and moderate
Hutu massacred in 1994.

00:10:17.600 --> 00:10:21.970
About 300,000 survivors,
with 58% women,

00:10:21.970 --> 00:10:27.740
64,000 or 65,000 orphans,
widows, rape victims, children

00:10:27.740 --> 00:10:31.000
born of rape, which is a major
issue right now in Rwanda,

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:32.700
and also handicapped.

00:10:32.700 --> 00:10:35.430
So these are some of
the scars that have

00:10:35.430 --> 00:10:38.800
been left after the genocide.

00:10:38.800 --> 00:10:40.730
So these are the
spaces of healing

00:10:40.730 --> 00:10:42.410
that I wanted to speak about.

00:10:42.410 --> 00:10:44.990
And I've identified
basically five categories,

00:10:44.990 --> 00:10:47.120
broad categories,
that I've really

00:10:47.120 --> 00:10:50.420
experienced that are taking
place in Rwanda today.

00:10:50.420 --> 00:10:54.650
And as I said, they have their
challenges and their successes.

00:10:54.650 --> 00:10:56.920
And what I really want
to do is to introduce you

00:10:56.920 --> 00:10:58.680
to those challenges
and successes

00:10:58.680 --> 00:11:02.020
so that we can gain a really
comprehensive understanding

00:11:02.020 --> 00:11:04.390
of how to even start
thinking about post-conflict

00:11:04.390 --> 00:11:05.370
development.

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:07.190
You won't be experts
by the end of the day

00:11:07.190 --> 00:11:10.230
but I'm hoping to give
you something to take away

00:11:10.230 --> 00:11:15.170
that will allow you to think
about how you envisioned

00:11:15.170 --> 00:11:18.200
post-conflict
societies and what you

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:20.580
might think after this lecture.

00:11:20.580 --> 00:11:24.900
So spaces of healing,
development, recovery, truth,

00:11:24.900 --> 00:11:30.610
and grief and Rwanda I've
identified as memory, justice,

00:11:30.610 --> 00:11:34.360
youth and education,
psychological health and trauma

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:37.210
healing, and technology
and research.

00:11:37.210 --> 00:11:40.187
I'm also not going to try to
give you the standard examples

00:11:40.187 --> 00:11:42.520
today, the ones that you've
read in the news or the ones

00:11:42.520 --> 00:11:43.976
that you've seen
a million times.

00:11:43.976 --> 00:11:45.600
What I'm going to
try to do is take you

00:11:45.600 --> 00:11:48.260
through my experiences
over the past four years

00:11:48.260 --> 00:11:49.980
and help, again, enter
into these spaces

00:11:49.980 --> 00:11:52.230
that are little known and
that you might not otherwise

00:11:52.230 --> 00:11:56.080
be able to see or access to help
us broaden our understanding.

00:11:56.080 --> 00:11:57.730
So I want you to
take a deep breath

00:11:57.730 --> 00:12:00.450
and look at this really
beautiful photo of a sunset

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:05.040
in Nyarubuye, Eastern Province,
Rwanda, where my godbrother is

00:12:05.040 --> 00:12:06.340
from and survived from.

00:12:06.340 --> 00:12:08.610
And I want you to just
take a minute before we

00:12:08.610 --> 00:12:10.330
enter into these themes.

00:12:10.330 --> 00:12:14.020
And think to yourself what
does post-conflict mean or look

00:12:14.020 --> 00:12:14.970
like?

00:12:14.970 --> 00:12:16.280
We saw those two photos.

00:12:16.280 --> 00:12:18.230
Does it look more
like the skulls?

00:12:18.230 --> 00:12:20.429
Does it look more like
the graduates, the women

00:12:20.429 --> 00:12:21.720
who have graduated high school?

00:12:21.720 --> 00:12:23.803
What does it look like to
you right now, before we

00:12:23.803 --> 00:12:24.930
enter into this moment?

00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:34.550
OK, I think we're ready.

00:12:34.550 --> 00:12:36.850
The first theme I want
to address is memory.

00:12:36.850 --> 00:12:39.100
And I want to
introduce you to Omar.

00:12:39.100 --> 00:12:43.460
This is Omar, who is standing in
Nyamata Memorial Church, where

00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:49.330
nearly 335,000 Rwandans were
massacred in early April 1994.

00:12:49.330 --> 00:12:54.380
And Omar, at 10 years old, was
only one of very few survivors.

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:58.930
As he was a child, he was able
to hide under other people

00:12:58.930 --> 00:13:04.390
who had already been killed,
and even was beaten on his legs

00:13:04.390 --> 00:13:08.350
and had to remain
silent basically

00:13:08.350 --> 00:13:11.650
to prove that he was dead before
