and never really knew

00:13:22.240 --> 00:13:24.090
about his survival story.

00:13:24.090 --> 00:13:26.990
But one day, we were
eating lunch in Kigali,

00:13:26.990 --> 00:13:29.000
and he said to me,
Samantha, I know

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.160
a lot about your work
documenting testimonies

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:35.570
and I'd like you to
come with me to Nyamata

00:13:35.570 --> 00:13:37.890
and to actually walk
through the site with me

00:13:37.890 --> 00:13:40.340
and document my story.

00:13:40.340 --> 00:13:41.990
And I thought to
myself, oh great.

00:13:41.990 --> 00:13:42.810
This is wonderful.

00:13:42.810 --> 00:13:44.190
It'll be good for my research.

00:13:44.190 --> 00:13:47.570
It will help my friend
Omar go through his story.

00:13:47.570 --> 00:13:49.870
But I didn't really
realize how incredibly

00:13:49.870 --> 00:13:52.420
difficult and
emotional it would be,

00:13:52.420 --> 00:13:55.860
not only returning to the site
but also returning to the site

00:13:55.860 --> 00:14:00.030
with a survivor of the site
who was also my friend.

00:14:00.030 --> 00:14:03.390
And so these issues
of memory were

00:14:03.390 --> 00:14:06.820
at play, not only the surface
issue where I can go in

00:14:06.820 --> 00:14:10.650
as a researcher and document
people's memories of the place,

00:14:10.650 --> 00:14:13.830
the second element is not only
am I documenting the memories

00:14:13.830 --> 00:14:18.400
but it was in the physical space
itself, which was very intense.

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:21.210
And the third element
was, this is my friend.

00:14:21.210 --> 00:14:23.880
This is someone I know and
care about and work with.

00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:27.360
So those three things
were at play in my mind

00:14:27.360 --> 00:14:31.360
as we began driving out of
Kigali toward Bugasara, where

00:14:31.360 --> 00:14:33.550
the Nyamata Memorial Church is.

00:14:33.550 --> 00:14:35.670
And in this photo,
Omar in the church.

00:14:35.670 --> 00:14:38.360
The gray banner is
a memorial banner,

00:14:38.360 --> 00:14:40.220
and he's looking down
at the benches which

00:14:40.220 --> 00:14:42.060
contain victims clothing.

00:14:42.060 --> 00:14:45.040
So those are clothing that
were either left in the church

00:14:45.040 --> 00:14:47.810
or brought to the
church from victims who

00:14:47.810 --> 00:14:49.100
had died during the genocide.

00:14:49.100 --> 00:14:51.220
And you can see he's thinking.

00:14:51.220 --> 00:14:54.930
And he's actually standing in
the place where he survived.

00:14:54.930 --> 00:14:57.950
He survived on the bench
that he is right in front of.

00:14:57.950 --> 00:15:01.850
And what was pretty
amazing about documenting

00:15:01.850 --> 00:15:05.880
Omar's story is the
kind of liberation

00:15:05.880 --> 00:15:07.870
it had for both me and for him.

00:15:07.870 --> 00:15:10.130
For me, I was trying
to be professional

00:15:10.130 --> 00:15:14.460
and not to cry when my
friend was telling me

00:15:14.460 --> 00:15:17.750
about his experiences,
which included listening

00:15:17.750 --> 00:15:19.910
to the children
and women who were

00:15:19.910 --> 00:15:23.540
at the back side of the church
by the altar, who were crying

00:15:23.540 --> 00:15:24.950
and screaming for God.

00:15:24.950 --> 00:15:28.060
He was hearing all of this
and was recounting this to us.

00:15:28.060 --> 00:15:32.180
And I felt like I
was causing him pain.

00:15:32.180 --> 00:15:35.050
I felt like I was poking
him with something sharp

00:15:35.050 --> 00:15:35.820
and hurting him.

00:15:35.820 --> 00:15:37.840
And I didn't want to
cause him any more pain,

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:39.630
but he had asked me
to do this and he

00:15:39.630 --> 00:15:42.070
wanted to document
the story and continue

00:15:42.070 --> 00:15:44.360
to take us throughout
the church and tell us

00:15:44.360 --> 00:15:45.620
about these experiences.

00:15:45.620 --> 00:15:47.910
And there I was, trying to
be completely professional

00:15:47.910 --> 00:15:50.990
for my friend but inside feeling
like I was really causing him

00:15:50.990 --> 00:15:54.440
pain and that was really
hard to deal with.

00:15:54.440 --> 00:15:57.590
And so we ended up recording
this in a video form,

00:15:57.590 --> 00:16:01.710
and Omar now has it to share
with his future family,

00:16:01.710 --> 00:16:03.265
future children, etc.

00:16:03.265 --> 00:16:05.730
And it ended up being a
really powerful experience

00:16:05.730 --> 00:16:08.200
but it took me really out of
my element where I usually

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:11.400
interview individuals
who I haven't met before

00:16:11.400 --> 00:16:15.330
and who I don't know and don't
have a prior relationship with,

00:16:15.330 --> 00:16:18.370
trying to understand their
relationship to memory

00:16:18.370 --> 00:16:20.510
and justice issues in Rwanda.

00:16:20.510 --> 00:16:21.820
So this was very different.

00:16:21.820 --> 00:16:26.020
And what it showed though was
how important the memory was

00:16:26.020 --> 00:16:28.320
to him, that he
wanted to do this

00:16:28.320 --> 00:16:31.420
as a way to honor his own
memory but also to keep it

00:16:31.420 --> 00:16:32.760
for the future.

00:16:32.760 --> 00:16:37.330
And so one of the themes
that I wanted to go through

00:16:37.330 --> 00:16:41.200
with memory is that
this Nyamata Memorial

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:45.540
site is one of the six national
memorial sites in Rwanda,

00:16:45.540 --> 00:16:48.510
and there are also many
the local memorial sites.

00:16:48.510 --> 00:16:50.820
They're often like this,
with survivor's clothing,

00:16:50.820 --> 00:16:56.450
skulls of survivors, caskets,
and other things left behind.

00:16:56.450 --> 00:17:01.000
But to bring in some of these
good things and the challenges,

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:02.790
I wanted to talk
about the purpose

00:17:02.790 --> 00:17:05.230
of having these memorial
sites and having

00:17:05.230 --> 00:17:07.470
annual commemorations
around them.

00:17:07.470 --> 00:17:10.109
So commemoration
period begins in Rwanda

00:17:10.109 --> 00:17:14.819
on April 7th every year and
lasts for about 100 days.

00:17:14.819 --> 00:17:18.230
And there are many local and
national commemorative events.

00:17:18.230 --> 00:17:21.660
And during the commemoration,
we have testimonies,

00:17:21.660 --> 00:17:25.480
poetry read, official
speakers from government

00:17:25.480 --> 00:17:29.150
and from other communities,
often a comparative lens.

00:17:29.150 --> 00:17:31.440
And most of the
population in Rwanda

00:17:31.440 --> 00:17:33.730
take part in these
commemorations.

00:17:33.730 --> 00:17:35.460
And so to get us
thinking, it's really

00:17:35.460 --> 00:17:37.920
about what is the purpose
of the commemoration?

00:17:37.920 --> 00:17:40.390
At one point, it brings
survivors together

00:17:40.390 --> 00:17:43.370
and it provides a validation
of the harms they've suffered.

00:17:43.370 --> 00:17:45.430
It can educate people.

00:17:45.430 --> 00:17:48.440
But sometimes there's also
this retraumatization.

00:17:48.440 --> 00:17:51.060
Sometimes, there are
state goals or other goals

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:53.610
that are at odds with
survivors' goals.

00:17:53.610 --> 00:17:55.950
And one survivor who
I spoke with last week

00:17:55.950 --> 00:17:58.010
when I was preparing
this told me

00:17:58.010 --> 00:18:01.540
that people can be in the same
physical commemoration spaces

00:18:01.540 --> 00:18:03.140
and be commemorating
and remembering

00:18:03.140 --> 00:18:05.470
different things, which I
think is something really

00:18:05.470 --> 00:18:07.400
interesting to think
about, how people

00:18:07.400 --> 00:18:09.710
can be experiencing
the same event

00:18:09.710 --> 00:18:12.912
yet be remembering it and
having different reactions.

00:18:12.912 --> 00:18:14.370
So that's one of
the challenges, is

00:18:14.370 --> 00:18:16.650
how to make
commemoration inclusive

00:18:16.650 --> 00:18:18.846
and bring everyone in.

00:18:18.846 --> 00:18:20.470
So this is, for
example, something that

00:18:20.470 --> 00:18:21.910
happens at the commemoration.

00:18:21.910 --> 00:18:24.410
This is a photo I took of
some of the candles that

00:18:24.410 --> 00:18:27.520
are lit as people sit in
these white plastic chairs.

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:30.600
And you could have anywhere
between 500 to 1,000 people

00:18:30.600 --> 00:18:32.040
at one commemoration.

00:18:32.040 --> 00:18:33.410
Sometimes, there could be 30.

00:18:33.410 --> 00:18:34.980
It depends on the
type but I just

00:18:34.980 --> 00:18:37.890
wanted to give you
a small perspective.

00:18:37.890 --> 00:18:41.880
The next thing I want to
talk about is justice.

00:18:41.880 --> 00:18:44.760
Justice is a huge, huge subject.

00:18:44.760 --> 00:18:46.220
And part of the
benefit of justice

00:18:46.220 --> 00:18:47.710
is that it is a large subject.

00:18:47.710 --> 00:18:50.560
So we don't have to be limited
in the ways in which we

00:18:50.560 --> 00:18:52.540
think about justice.

00:18:52.540 --> 00:18:54.690
And I know I'm not
going to do justice

00:18:54.690 --> 00:18:57.520
to the subject of
justice today, but I

00:18:57.520 --> 00:18:59.480
do want to give you a
little bit of history

00:18:59.480 --> 00:19:01.450
and take you into the spaces.

00:19:01.450 --> 00:19:03.820
So again, this Nyamata
Memorial Church.

00:19:03.820 --> 00:19:05.440
You can see those
benches and you

00:19:05.440 --> 00:19:10.740
can see the wreaths that have
been laid on the ground there.

00:19:10.740 --> 00:19:14.430
So this is a bigger
picture of the church.

00:19:14.430 --> 00:19:17.600
So memorial sites are a
form of symbolic justice,

00:19:17.600 --> 00:19:19.710
which is one way
to bring justice,

00:19:19.710 --> 00:19:21.380
especially to survivors.

00:19:21.380 --> 00:19:24.690
So in transitional justice,
we often think about courts.

00:19:24.690 --> 00:19:27.400
We think about international
criminal tribunals.

00:19:27.400 --> 00:19:28.860
We think about local courts.

00:19:28.860 --> 00:19:32.130
We think about the court system
when we think about justice.

00:19:32.130 --> 00:19:33.730
Automatically, when
we say justice,

00:19:33.730 --> 00:19:36.120
our mind goes to the
lawyers, and to the judges,

00:19:36.120 --> 00:19:37.750
and to the court systems.

00:19:37.750 --> 00:19:41.010
Which is good, and there are
many, many positive benefits

00:19:41.010 --> 00:19:43.950
from the court systems,
including holding perpetrators

00:19:43.950 --> 00:19:45.450
accountable.

00:19:45.450 --> 00:19:48.420
One of the things,
though, that I focus on

00:19:48.420 --> 00:19:50.400
is what happens when
the courts close

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:53.450
and when there is no
longer juridical justice.

00:19:53.450 --> 00:19:56.290
And that's where these symbolic
efforts, such as apology,

00:19:56.290 --> 00:19:58.010
and memorialization,
and commemorations

00:19:58.010 --> 00:20:00.940
come into play, which really
focus less on perpetrators

00:20:00.940 --> 00:20:02.810
and more on survivors.

00:20:02.810 --> 00:20:07.370
I just want to go through a
story of a woman, Bernadette,

00:20:07.370 --> 00:20:13.220
who I met interviewing during my
fifth research trip in Rwanda.

00:20:13.220 --> 00:20:16.660
And we were sitting on the
grass at the back of the Nyamata

00:20:16.660 --> 00:20:18.840
Memorial Church.

00:20:18.840 --> 00:20:20.420
It had been an
hour long bus ride

00:20:20.420 --> 00:20:23.320
and we really had come,
my interpreter and I,

00:20:23.320 --> 00:20:25.780
just to interview Bernadette.

00:20:25.780 --> 00:20:29.560
Now, Bernadette was a
caretaker at the memorial,

00:20:29.560 --> 00:20:32.100
and most people didn't
pay attention to her.

00:20:32.100 --> 00:20:33.700
They didn't know
about her story.

00:20:33.700 --> 00:20:37.010
But when I met her and started
speaking a bit of Kinyarwanda

00:20:37.010 --> 00:20:38.910
with her, I realized
she had a lot more

00:20:38.910 --> 00:20:43.060
to discuss than
might have let on

00:20:43.060 --> 00:20:45.250
with her basically
being a janitor,

00:20:45.250 --> 00:20:46.820
having a cleaning role.

00:20:46.820 --> 00:20:51.020
And I remember this day sitting
barefoot on the grass there,

00:20:51.020 --> 00:20:55.260
the three women, me, my
interpreter, and Bernadette,

00:20:55.260 --> 00:20:58.080
asking questions about
memory and justice.

00:20:58.080 --> 00:21:02.200
And she told me,
basically, that she

00:21:02.200 --> 00:21:08.110
had been hiding in a place that
was unfit for any human being.

00:21:08.110 --> 00:21:11.720
She was hiding in a
hole in the ground

00:21:11.720 --> 00:21:14.920
underneath some
large banana leaves.

00:21:14.920 --> 00:21:18.580
And the Rwandan Patriotic
Front eventually found her.

00:21:18.580 --> 00:21:22.350
And she remembers them
picking her out of there

00:21:22.350 --> 00:21:26.750
and bringing her to a safe
spot and picking the bugs out

00:21:26.750 --> 00:21:28.430
of her clothes and hair.

00:21:28.430 --> 00:21:31.500
And she defines this as
her sense of justice, which

00:21:31.500 --> 00:21:33.490
is the human decency
that she was treated

00:21:33.490 --> 00:21:35.810
with in that moment
of despair, when

00:21:35.810 --> 00:21:39.240
she thought that the world
had forgotten about her.

00:21:39.240 --> 00:21:41.860
And so it's from
that perspective

00:21:41.860 --> 00:21:44.720
that I take an
understanding of justice,

00:21:44.720 --> 00:21:46.520
that justice can have
multiple meanings

00:21:46.520 --> 00:21:50.630
for people in the aftermath
of genocide and conflict.

00:21:50.630 --> 00:21:53.500
In addition to those
legal forms of justice,

00:21:53.500 --> 00:21:56.060
we also have many
other forms of justice

00:21:56.060 --> 00:21:59.410
that we may not even know about
or may not even know to ask.

00:21:59.410 --> 00:22:01.270
And one of the things
I do in my research

00:22:01.270 --> 00:22:05.240
is try to get at those other
forms and other definitions

00:22:05.240 --> 00:22:09.440
of justice that may provide
more meaning for policy

00:22:09.440 --> 00:22:13.730
and reconciliation programs
than the traditional forms

00:22:13.730 --> 00:22:14.350
of justice.

00:22:14.350 --> 00:22:17.130
So just something for us
to think about, again.

00:22:17.130 --> 00:22:20.640
These are children at the
Nyamata Memorial Church, who

00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:23.870
are going on an
official commemoration,

00:22:23.870 --> 00:22:27.670
bringing their wreath,
which is really

00:22:27.670 --> 00:22:30.820
a common thing in Rwanda.

00:22:30.820 --> 00:22:33.320
The next theme I want to talk
about is youth and education.

00:22:33.320 --> 00:22:35.500
So this has Gakire,
Dieudonne Gakire.

00:22:35.500 --> 00:22:38.780
And I met Dieudonne
Gakire through a friend.

00:22:38.780 --> 00:22:40.970
Gakire is the author of
"A Dreaming Child," which

00:22:40.970 --> 00:22:45.760
is this phenomenal book about
young people's experiences

00:22:45.760 --> 00:22:47.660
during the genocide in Rwanda.

00:22:47.660 --> 00:22:51.010
And I bring up
Gakire because he is

00:22:51.010 --> 00:22:53.130
quite representative
of the roles

00:22:53.130 --> 00:22:57.670
that young people had to take in
the aftermath of the genocide.

00:22:57.670 --> 00:23:00.070
Now, not every young person
is interested in the history

00:23:00.070 --> 00:23:00.750
of genocide.

00:23:00.750 --> 00:23:02.330
And that's normal.

00:23:02.330 --> 00:23:05.000
But there are many people
in Rwanda, especially young

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:06.880
people, who are truly
interested in trying

00:23:06.880 --> 00:23:10.190
to make sense and have
this psychological process

00:23:10.190 --> 00:23:13.370
of meaning making of the
experiences they had,

00:23:13.370 --> 00:23:16.404
whether they were two years old,
four years old, 10 years old,

00:23:16.404 --> 00:23:17.820
they're still
trying to make sense

00:23:17.820 --> 00:23:19.490
of what happened
to their families

00:23:19.490 --> 00:23:20.760
and also educate others.

00:23:20.760 --> 00:23:23.990
And they really take
this as a personal goal.

00:23:23.990 --> 00:23:27.290
And Gakire's curious book
is an example of that.

00:23:27.290 --> 00:23:29.790
Gakire was actually
invited to Bogota, Colombia

00:23:29.790 --> 00:23:32.897
to attend the international
book fair there.

00:23:32.897 --> 00:23:34.980
And I had been working
with him on getting grants.

00:23:34.980 --> 00:23:37.320
And thanks to a
number of sponsors,

00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:41.080
he was able to fly for the first
time out of Rwanda to Bogota.

00:23:41.080 --> 00:23:43.997
And I remember being
on Facebook Messenger,

00:23:43.997 --> 00:23:45.080
and I said, how did it go?

00:23:45.080 --> 00:23:46.760
How was the lecture?

00:23:46.760 --> 00:23:50.480
And he said, there
were 400 people there.

00:23:50.480 --> 00:23:54.150
And I thought to myself,
400 people from Colombia

00:23:54.150 --> 00:23:58.660
and other places came to hear
you speak about your book?

00:23:58.660 --> 00:24:01.990
That's pretty incredible, and
the impact is pretty amazing.

00:24:01.990 --> 00:24:04.540
And just to provide
a statistic, 60%

00:24:04.540 --> 00:24:07.380
of Rwandans living in Rwanda
are under the age of 25,

00:24:07.380 --> 00:24:08.010
like Gakire.

00:24:08.010 --> 00:24:14.060
And so we have this heavy
burden but also opportunity

00:24:14.060 --> 00:24:16.039
put on the youth in Rwanda.

00:24:16.039 --> 00:24:17.580
And there are other
incredible things

00:24:17.580 --> 00:24:20.910
that they're doing that I
can tell you about as well.

00:24:20.910 --> 00:24:23.370
I also want to
introduce you to Henry.

00:24:23.370 --> 00:24:26.255
Henry is one of those graduates
of Agahozo-Shalom Youth

00:24:26.255 --> 00:24:27.330
Village in Rwanda.

00:24:27.330 --> 00:24:29.510
You can see his
green cap and gown.

00:24:29.510 --> 00:24:33.680
And I met Henry on my
first visit, first weekend

00:24:33.680 --> 00:24:37.120
in Rwanda, where I was
invited to the youth village

00:24:37.120 --> 00:24:40.570
to attend their science fair.

00:24:40.570 --> 00:24:43.500
And Henry was
actually put in charge

00:24:43.500 --> 00:24:46.180
of the welcoming committee,
and he welcomed me as a guest.

00:24:46.180 --> 00:24:47.200
He didn't know me.

00:24:47.200 --> 00:24:48.730
I didn't know him.

00:24:48.730 --> 00:24:50.900
Those relationships you
think, OK, they're passing.

00:24:50.900 --> 00:24:51.733
I'll meet him.

00:24:51.733 --> 00:24:52.274
I'll go back.

00:24:52.274 --> 00:24:53.610
I'll start my work.

00:24:53.610 --> 00:24:55.310
It'll be fine.

00:24:55.310 --> 00:24:58.170
It turned out that I gave
Henry my e-mail address,

00:24:58.170 --> 00:25:01.110
and he started to write to me
as he began to apply to colleges

00:25:01.110 --> 00:25:02.290
and asked me advice.

00:25:02.290 --> 00:25:04.500
And I was very apt
to work with him.

00:25:04.500 --> 00:25:06.750
He is an incredible young man.

00:25:06.750 --> 00:25:11.450
And basically,
three years later,

00:25:11.450 --> 00:25:16.100
Henry is now a second year
student at McGill University.

00:25:16.100 --> 00:25:18.980
Not only did he gain admission,
but he gained scholarships

00:25:18.980 --> 00:25:21.500
from McGill and from
private families.

00:25:21.500 --> 00:25:24.620
And we worked together in order
to make this dream come true.

00:25:24.620 --> 00:25:27.320
And it was pretty amazing,
because I can't tell you

00:25:27.320 --> 00:25:29.830
the amount of times
that I said "Henry, I'm

00:25:29.830 --> 00:25:31.640
sure this is going
to happen this year."

00:25:31.640 --> 00:25:34.582
I said, "maybe in future
years, but as you know,

00:25:34.582 --> 00:25:37.180
college in the West
is very expensive."

00:25:37.180 --> 00:25:39.810
And coming from a background
where both of his parents

00:25:39.810 --> 00:25:43.280
were killed during the genocide,
while his mother was actually

00:25:43.280 --> 00:25:46.810
breastfeeding him and had
his twin brother on the back.

00:25:46.810 --> 00:25:48.110
He has a twin.

00:25:48.110 --> 00:25:51.590
And what was amazing
was, I was sitting

00:25:51.590 --> 00:25:54.390
with these two boys on their
birthday having dinner.

00:25:54.390 --> 00:25:56.210
And his brother,
Eric, said to me,

00:25:56.210 --> 00:25:58.026
"Do you believe in miracles?"

00:25:58.026 --> 00:25:59.904
And I thought to myself,
I don't really know.

00:25:59.904 --> 00:26:01.570
I don't think about
miracles that often.

00:26:01.570 --> 00:26:03.370
And he said, "Well,
can you imagine

00:26:03.370 --> 00:26:06.340
that a boy from this
background in Rwanda growing up

00:26:06.340 --> 00:26:10.230
with a grandmother in a
pretty poor neighborhood

00:26:10.230 --> 00:26:13.010
is heading off to
McGill in a few weeks

00:26:13.010 --> 00:26:16.230
with his visa, his
scholarship, his apartment,

00:26:16.230 --> 00:26:17.480
and everything sorted out?"

00:26:17.480 --> 00:26:19.780
And I said, "Yeah, it's
pretty incredible."

00:26:19.780 --> 00:26:22.480
And he looked at me and
said, "No, this is a miracle.

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:23.860
It's not just
pretty incredible."

00:26:23.860 --> 00:26:26.330
And so he really
changed my perspective.

00:26:26.330 --> 00:26:28.770
But Henry and I are in
touch on a weekly basis,

00:26:28.770 --> 00:26:32.310
and I'll be working with him
throughout his entire college

00:26:32.310 --> 00:26:33.120
experience.

00:26:33.120 --> 00:26:35.570
And I'm excited for
the opportunities

00:26:35.570 --> 00:26:39.290
that youth have both
in Rwanda and out.

00:26:39.290 --> 00:26:43.140
The last thing I want to mention
about youth is peace education.

00:26:43.140 --> 00:26:45.480
And very, very briefly,
the organization

00:26:45.480 --> 00:26:48.400
I used to work for, Aegis
Trust and the Kigali Genocide

00:26:48.400 --> 00:26:51.600
Memorial, started this
educational program

00:26:51.600 --> 00:26:54.450
around peace and critical
thinking for youth.

00:26:54.450 --> 00:26:57.690
And this is another aspect of
post-genocide and post-conflict

00:26:57.690 --> 00:27:02.070
recovery is how to reeducate
and help youth really understand

00:27:02.070 --> 00:27:04.870
the power of their
decisions and make sure

00:27:04.870 --> 00:27:06.990
that they can both understand
their past in order

00:27:06.990 --> 00:27:08.730
to go forward to the future.

00:27:08.730 --> 00:27:10.640
So this shows the
story of Eduard,

00:27:10.640 --> 00:27:14.270
who is one of the upstanders
during the genocide.

00:27:14.270 --> 00:27:17.700
And through pictures
and this exhibit,

00:27:17.700 --> 00:27:22.720
and these graphic designs take
students through his story.

00:27:22.720 --> 00:27:24.850
And then afterward, they
sit with facilitators

00:27:24.850 --> 00:27:28.300
and go through some of the
main themes about, as I said,

00:27:28.300 --> 00:27:31.250
critical thinking, the
power of individual choice,

00:27:31.250 --> 00:27:34.630
and the power of living together
in the aftermath of conflict.

00:27:37.530 --> 00:27:39.350
So the next thing
I want to touch on

00:27:39.350 --> 00:27:43.330
is psychological healing
and trauma healing.

00:27:43.330 --> 00:27:45.655
And as I said, I'm not
going to tell you completely

00:27:45.655 --> 00:27:48.420
the standard stories.

00:27:48.420 --> 00:27:51.410
This is a picture I
took when I saw and met

00:27:51.410 --> 00:27:58.585
the all-female drumming
group, whose name is Ingoma

00:27:58.585 --> 00:28:00.550
Nshya which means "a new drum."

00:28:00.550 --> 00:28:06.450
And so drumming in Rwanda is
traditionally reserved for men

00:28:06.450 --> 00:28:09.650
and prohibited from
women, who are usually

00:28:09.650 --> 00:28:11.850
prohibited from even
touching drums or even

00:28:11.850 --> 00:28:15.410
approaching the drummer who
used to perform for the king.

00:28:15.410 --> 00:28:18.140
But this drum group came
about after the genocide,

00:28:18.140 --> 00:28:20.480
with Hutu and Tutsi
women coming together

00:28:20.480 --> 00:28:23.100
of all different ages,
of different backgrounds,

00:28:23.100 --> 00:28:26.360
of socioeconomic backgrounds,
other backgrounds,

00:28:26.360 --> 00:28:29.860
came together to learn
this and actually

00:28:29.860 --> 00:28:33.020
to show that they are strong,
both physically in picking up

00:28:33.020 --> 00:28:35.050
the drums and actually
drumming, and also

00:28:35.050 --> 00:28:37.510
that they're strong
mentally and emotionally.

00:28:37.510 --> 00:28:39.290
And this is a very
interesting example

00:28:39.290 --> 00:28:41.665
of psychological health,
because it's not what we usually

00:28:41.665 --> 00:28:44.230
think of, where people
sit in counseling groups

00:28:44.230 --> 00:28:47.170
for individual counseling,
which takes a long time

00:28:47.170 --> 00:28:51.050
and is very slow and is
also costly and expensive.

00:28:51.050 --> 00:28:54.920
There are amazing things about
this kind of trauma counseling,

00:28:54.920 --> 00:28:56.880
but in Rwanda, many
people don't access it.

00:28:56.880 --> 00:29:00.650
And so these kinds of groups
which bring people together

00:29:00.650 --> 00:29:02.060
are pretty incredible.

00:29:02.060 --> 00:29:03.920
And after I saw
this performance,

00:29:03.920 --> 00:29:06.050
I spoke to one of the
drummers and she basically

00:29:06.050 --> 00:29:09.110
said, "You know, the group
is like a new family."

00:29:09.110 --> 00:29:12.140
Rwandans, a lot of them
lost family, if not

00:29:12.140 --> 00:29:15.400
entire members of their
family during the genocide.

00:29:15.400 --> 00:29:17.440
And these newly
constructed social groups

00:29:17.440 --> 00:29:18.860
and social networks
are incredibly

00:29:18.860 --> 00:29:21.860
important for psychological
health and trauma healing,

00:29:21.860 --> 00:29:23.580
because the women
also talk about what's

00:29:23.580 --> 00:29:25.110
going on in their lives.

00:29:25.110 --> 00:29:28.560
They celebrate together,
weddings, births, deaths.

00:29:28.560 --> 00:29:31.590
Everything that you would expect
a family or a broader community

00:29:31.590 --> 00:29:33.396
to do, these women do together.

00:29:33.396 --> 00:29:34.770
And there are
others and examples

00:29:34.770 --> 00:29:37.680
of these kinds of groups
around economic development

00:29:37.680 --> 00:29:41.180
and other development
that have this benefit

00:29:41.180 --> 00:29:43.450
of psychological healing.

00:29:43.450 --> 00:29:44.850
This is a photo
that was actually

00:29:44.850 --> 00:29:48.410
taken by a very
close friend of mine

00:29:48.410 --> 00:29:51.020
who is a professional
photographer in Rwanda.

00:29:51.020 --> 00:29:52.700
And if you look
closely, the photo

00:29:52.700 --> 00:29:57.020
is of a scar on the stomach
of someone in Rwanda.

00:29:57.020 --> 00:30:01.220
And I interviewed this person
about a year and a half ago.

00:30:01.220 --> 00:30:04.990
And he was very shy, very quiet.

00:30:04.990 --> 00:30:08.100
The interview didn't
last very long.

00:30:08.100 --> 00:30:09.910
But one of the things
that really struck me

00:30:09.910 --> 00:30:11.860
was this discussion of scars.

00:30:11.860 --> 00:30:15.150
And I spoke to him
and said-- he told me

00:30:15.150 --> 00:30:19.720
he was captured Interahamwe
and had some scars.

00:30:19.720 --> 00:30:22.310
And I said to him,
can you tell me

00:30:22.310 --> 00:30:23.670
a little bit about your scars?

00:30:23.670 --> 00:30:27.800
And what he did was he stood
up and he lifted up his shirt

00:30:27.800 --> 00:30:31.305
and showed me this
scar on his stomach.

00:30:31.305 --> 00:30:32.680
After meeting him
the first time,

00:30:32.680 --> 00:30:34.230
I went back to
interview him again,

00:30:34.230 --> 00:30:38.210
but I was shocked at the
kind of vulnerability

00:30:38.210 --> 00:30:41.500
of showing this
white woman in Rwanda

00:30:41.500 --> 00:30:44.520
this scar on his stomach.

00:30:44.520 --> 00:30:46.800
But he wanted to
make a statement,

00:30:46.800 --> 00:30:50.590
which is that some of
the scars you can see,

00:30:50.590 --> 00:30:52.970
both the psychological
and the physical scars,

00:30:52.970 --> 00:30:54.462
and some you can't.

00:30:54.462 --> 00:30:55.920
Some are hidden
under your clothes.

00:30:55.920 --> 00:30:58.180
Some are hidden in your mind.

00:30:58.180 --> 00:31:03.180
Some are hidden until something
triggers them and comes out.

00:31:03.180 --> 00:31:05.240
But the scars are living
with these people,

00:31:05.240 --> 00:31:08.770
are living with Rwandans,
and we don't know necessarily

00:31:08.770 --> 00:31:12.020
when they're going to manifest
themselves or in what ways.

00:31:12.020 --> 00:31:14.930
And so when working in
post-conflict societies,

00:31:14.930 --> 00:31:17.810
we have to be very,
very almost vigilant

00:31:17.810 --> 00:31:22.510
to the point of respect
that we can understand,

00:31:22.510 --> 00:31:25.850
coming from non-survivor
perspectives,

00:31:25.850 --> 00:31:29.150
how to work with
survivors and others,

00:31:29.150 --> 00:31:32.220
including perpetrators,
who have of what happened

00:31:32.220 --> 00:31:33.730
and what they have done.

00:31:33.730 --> 00:31:35.440
Now, I personally
believe that all of us

00:31:35.440 --> 00:31:39.590
have suffered some form of
trauma or some negative thing.

00:31:39.590 --> 00:31:42.530
And it's not about comparing
hierarchies of suffering.

00:31:42.530 --> 00:31:45.610
What happened to me is
not necessarily as bad

00:31:45.610 --> 00:31:48.120
or doesn't feel as bad
as what happened to you

00:31:48.120 --> 00:31:50.290
or what happened to a
survivor, but the point

00:31:50.290 --> 00:31:53.260
is figuring out what is the
human level that we can connect

00:31:53.260 --> 00:31:55.740
on to show the most
basic level of respect

00:31:55.740 --> 00:31:58.550
for someone who's been
through these experiences.

00:31:58.550 --> 00:32:04.250
And I've been very lucky to
have had the opportunity to see

00:32:04.250 --> 00:32:06.980
scars like these, which
definitely make you

00:32:06.980 --> 00:32:09.940
uncomfortable to have
them photographed and used

00:32:09.940 --> 00:32:12.480
for educational
purposes, for teaching,

00:32:12.480 --> 00:32:16.710
and also to understand that,
again, the scars don't always

00:32:16.710 --> 00:32:18.610
come at the same time.

00:32:18.610 --> 00:32:20.700
And so one thing I wanted
to mention about scars

00:32:20.700 --> 00:32:23.210
as well is during
the 1994-- I'm sorry,

00:32:23.210 --> 00:32:26.160
during the commemoration
period that starts on April 7th

00:32:26.160 --> 00:32:31.320
every year, I often get texts
on WhatsApp or on text message

00:32:31.320 --> 00:32:34.645
and say, "You know, Samantha,
I'm not doing well."

00:32:34.645 --> 00:32:36.770
And I get a little concerned
and I think to myself,

00:32:36.770 --> 00:32:39.810
"Well, I'm not a counselor,
and I've met people in Rwanda

00:32:39.810 --> 00:32:42.590
and they're telling me that all
of a sudden something happened

00:32:42.590 --> 00:32:44.210
and they're not doing well."

00:32:44.210 --> 00:32:46.520
And so it's very
surprising the ways

00:32:46.520 --> 00:32:49.350
in which people will
reach out to their friends

00:32:49.350 --> 00:32:51.129
and other people
who they've met.

00:32:51.129 --> 00:32:53.420
And sometimes you feel I
don't have a strong connection

00:32:53.420 --> 00:32:55.430
with that person
but for some reason

00:32:55.430 --> 00:32:57.150
they felt they could
trust me or maybe I

00:32:57.150 --> 00:32:58.514
was the only one online, right?

00:32:58.514 --> 00:33:00.430
Maybe I was the only one
online in that moment

00:33:00.430 --> 00:33:02.320
and they wanted to
speak to someone.

00:33:02.320 --> 00:33:04.680
But letting them know
I'm not a counselor

00:33:04.680 --> 00:33:05.730
but I'm here as a friend.

00:33:05.730 --> 00:33:07.450
I can advise you
in that capacity.

00:33:07.450 --> 00:33:10.520
But it's amazing the amount
of text messages and messages

00:33:10.520 --> 00:33:12.680
I get during this period.

00:33:12.680 --> 00:33:16.290
And the emotional stress both
on the individual and myself,

00:33:16.290 --> 00:33:20.140
just being very completely
honest and vulnerable with you,

00:33:20.140 --> 00:33:25.400
but that's the responsibility
of working in this sector,

00:33:25.400 --> 00:33:28.410
is to accept these
relationships as they are

00:33:28.410 --> 00:33:33.150
and to try your best
to do what you can do.

00:33:33.150 --> 00:33:39.000
And none of us is perfect
but even just being there

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:40.690
for someone is sometimes enough.

00:33:40.690 --> 00:33:43.360
I had someone write to
me very late at night

00:33:43.360 --> 00:33:45.940
and in the morning
wrote back and said, "I

00:33:45.940 --> 00:33:50.362
was thinking of overdrinking.

00:33:50.362 --> 00:33:52.070
And after I spoke to
you, I went to sleep

00:33:52.070 --> 00:33:54.596
and I realized that I would
wake up tomorrow and feel maybe

00:33:54.596 --> 00:33:55.470
a little bit better."

00:33:55.470 --> 00:33:58.760
And all I did was take a
minute to communicate with him.

00:33:58.760 --> 00:34:01.764
And I didn't know about any
of these thoughts in his mind,

00:34:01.764 --> 00:34:04.180
but what was pretty incredible
was just taking that moment

00:34:04.180 --> 00:34:05.138
to say, "Yes, I'm here.

00:34:05.138 --> 00:34:05.975
Tell me what's up.

00:34:05.975 --> 00:34:07.310
I'm going t have to
go in a couple minutes

00:34:07.310 --> 00:34:08.185
to get back to work."

00:34:08.185 --> 00:34:10.400
But whatever it
is, sometimes you

00:34:10.400 --> 00:34:12.070
don't know the impact
of the people who

00:34:12.070 --> 00:34:14.989
you are interacting with.

00:34:14.989 --> 00:34:17.750
So the last point I want to
touch on is an uplifting point

00:34:17.750 --> 00:34:20.150
and is definitely
appropriate for those

00:34:20.150 --> 00:34:23.219
of you working at Google
and working in this sector,

00:34:23.219 --> 00:34:24.820
is technology and research.

00:34:24.820 --> 00:34:28.460
And one of the things that
has been happening in Rwanda

00:34:28.460 --> 00:34:31.139
is the startup
company of Safe Motos.

00:34:31.139 --> 00:34:34.370
So Safe Motos has helped
Rwanda separate good drivers

00:34:34.370 --> 00:34:36.550
from what they call
the crazy ones.

00:34:36.550 --> 00:34:41.370
Motorbikes are a very
common way to get around

00:34:41.370 --> 00:34:44.250
in Rwanda, especially in
the capital city of Kigali.

00:34:44.250 --> 00:34:46.489
And most of the motorbikes
are unregistered

00:34:46.489 --> 00:34:49.380
and most accidents also
happen on motorbikes.

00:34:49.380 --> 00:34:51.889
And so Safe Motos
has an app that's

00:34:51.889 --> 00:34:55.610
very similar to Uber that
encourages motorbike taxi

00:34:55.610 --> 00:35:00.920
riders to contact Safe Motos,
whose moto drivers are trained

00:35:00.920 --> 00:35:02.770
in safety, and
there's also a record

00:35:02.770 --> 00:35:04.610
given on how many
accidents they've had

00:35:04.610 --> 00:35:06.950
and what kind of driving
record they have.

00:35:06.950 --> 00:35:10.130
So not only are you able to
be picked up in a safe place,

00:35:10.130 --> 00:35:13.730
but you're also able to know
the rating of your driver,

00:35:13.730 --> 00:35:16.000
again, very similar to Uber.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:19.440
The two founders, Peter
Kariuki and Barrett Nash.

00:35:19.440 --> 00:35:21.480
Peter is actually a
close friend of mine,

00:35:21.480 --> 00:35:25.250
and they're doing
amazing, amazing work.

00:35:25.250 --> 00:35:30.030
And they also are interested
because belonging to Safe Motos

00:35:30.030 --> 00:35:33.090
not only helps the rider but
actually helps the driver.

00:35:33.090 --> 00:35:36.120
And moto drivers are
one of these segments

00:35:36.120 --> 00:35:38.899
of the population that you don't
really know a lot about them.

00:35:38.899 --> 00:35:40.440
You don't know if
they're a survivor.

00:35:40.440 --> 00:35:42.730
You have no idea if they
were a former perpetrator.

00:35:42.730 --> 00:35:45.060
Oftentimes, they don't
speak English or French.

00:35:45.060 --> 00:35:47.800
It's hard for Westerners
to communicate with them

00:35:47.800 --> 00:35:50.330
but they are a huge
segment of the population.

00:35:50.330 --> 00:35:52.990
Many of them are coming from
villages or other places

00:35:52.990 --> 00:35:55.910
to the capital city of
Kigali to drive a motorbike

00:35:55.910 --> 00:35:57.150
and make money.

00:35:57.150 --> 00:35:59.514
And so they're one of
the people that we really

00:35:59.514 --> 00:36:01.180
don't know a lot
about, groups of people

00:36:01.180 --> 00:36:02.930
that we really don't
know a lot about

00:36:02.930 --> 00:36:06.190
but are heavily prevalent
in society in Kigali.

00:36:06.190 --> 00:36:10.020
And so one of the amazing things
is that authorities are often

00:36:10.020 --> 00:36:14.030
ambivalent towards moto
drivers, as they associate them

00:36:14.030 --> 00:36:15.710
with crime and disorder.

00:36:15.710 --> 00:36:19.430
But becoming part
of Safe Motos helps

00:36:19.430 --> 00:36:21.880
them show that they're
legitimate people just trying

00:36:21.880 --> 00:36:23.680
to make an income
and really helps

00:36:23.680 --> 00:36:25.910
them gain legitimacy in
the eyes of authorities,

00:36:25.910 --> 00:36:28.010
in the eyes of the
rest of society.

00:36:28.010 --> 00:36:29.680
So it actually
has a dual purpose

00:36:29.680 --> 00:36:32.450
in helping people ride
safely and reduce accidents

00:36:32.450 --> 00:36:34.550
but also helping in
societal recovery,

00:36:34.550 --> 00:36:37.550
showing that these moto drivers
are not young men coming

00:36:37.550 --> 00:36:39.720
to create problems in the
city but they're actually

00:36:39.720 --> 00:36:42.761
just trying to make a living
in the best way that they can.

00:36:42.761 --> 00:36:46.630
And you can even see this is a
free concert, an advertisement

00:36:46.630 --> 00:36:48.710
that says ride with
Safe Motos there.

00:36:48.710 --> 00:36:50.160
So they're doing
their advertising

00:36:50.160 --> 00:36:52.681
and saying, "You want
to come to this concert?

00:36:52.681 --> 00:36:53.180
Great.

00:36:53.180 --> 00:36:54.100
Ride with Safe Motos.

00:36:54.100 --> 00:36:55.830
Be safe on your way."

00:36:55.830 --> 00:36:57.130
It's an amazing initiative.

00:36:57.130 --> 00:36:59.070
There's been a lot of
press on Safe Motos

00:36:59.070 --> 00:37:01.700
and they've become a
pretty incredible startup.

00:37:01.700 --> 00:37:04.060
But I think what's
amazing about them

00:37:04.060 --> 00:37:06.470
is their commitment to
developing the sector of moto

00:37:06.470 --> 00:37:09.590
drivers within the
post-conflict society

00:37:09.590 --> 00:37:15.310
to get rid of this concept of
the young men trying to cause

00:37:15.310 --> 00:37:18.380
problems in this city, which
is a theoretical concept

00:37:18.380 --> 00:37:20.620
in post-conflict societies,
that the young men come

00:37:20.620 --> 00:37:22.800
to the cities and they
want to cause problems

00:37:22.800 --> 00:37:24.930
and they don't have
homes or education.

00:37:24.930 --> 00:37:28.730
And this is combating
that stereotype.

00:37:28.730 --> 00:37:30.680
And the last thing
I want to mention,

00:37:30.680 --> 00:37:36.670
bringing it back to
memory and technology,

00:37:36.670 --> 00:37:40.840
is the Genocide Archive
of Rwanda's new web page.

00:37:40.840 --> 00:37:43.900
And so the Genocide
Archive of Rwanda

00:37:43.900 --> 00:37:47.090
is able to bring access and
knowledge to individuals

00:37:47.090 --> 00:37:49.030
around the world.

00:37:49.030 --> 00:37:53.150
They have prescanned and
prescreened all of their data

00:37:53.150 --> 00:37:55.810
that they put online, where
people can watch videos.

00:37:55.810 --> 00:38:00.050
They can watch propaganda videos
of the Hutu hardline regimes

00:38:00.050 --> 00:38:01.660
before 1994.

00:38:01.660 --> 00:38:03.200
They can find documents.

00:38:03.200 --> 00:38:06.120
They can take a virtual tour
of the memorial sites, which

00:38:06.120 --> 00:38:08.682
is pretty incredible.

00:38:08.682 --> 00:38:10.390
And these are some of
the positive things

00:38:10.390 --> 00:38:13.040
about this website.

00:38:13.040 --> 00:38:17.780
And some of the questions
also exists, which is how

00:38:17.780 --> 00:38:19.440
or in what ways can
they be meaningful

00:38:19.440 --> 00:38:21.220
for the local community
on the ground?

00:38:21.220 --> 00:38:23.790
They have a huge reach for
people who are international

00:38:23.790 --> 00:38:26.409
but what about survivors,
perpetrators, ordinary citizens

00:38:26.409 --> 00:38:28.200
who are living on the
ground, who might not

00:38:28.200 --> 00:38:30.790
have internet access,
or who might not

00:38:30.790 --> 00:38:33.220
be interested in this
kind of education?

00:38:33.220 --> 00:38:36.120
Who is their primary audience
and how do these issues

00:38:36.120 --> 00:38:38.730
reconcile themselves on the
same platform, the issue

00:38:38.730 --> 00:38:40.760
of catering to a
number of communities

00:38:40.760 --> 00:38:43.206
and a number of individuals?

00:38:43.206 --> 00:38:45.830
And so that's one of the things
that I think about when looking

00:38:45.830 --> 00:38:49.000
at these online platforms or
these virtual tours of sites is

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:52.999
that, yes, a lot of people
cannot travel to Rwanda and see

00:38:52.999 --> 00:38:55.040
these sites firsthand or
understand what happened

00:38:55.040 --> 00:38:55.680
firsthand.

00:38:55.680 --> 00:38:57.270
So they're getting
wonderful education

00:38:57.270 --> 00:39:00.772
through a platform like the
Genocide Archive of Rwanda.

00:39:00.772 --> 00:39:02.230
But at the same
time, we don't want

00:39:02.230 --> 00:39:05.560
to do that at the expense
of understanding and making

00:39:05.560 --> 00:39:10.190
memorials and other archives
meaningful for survivors

00:39:10.190 --> 00:39:13.290
and former perpetrators.

00:39:13.290 --> 00:39:15.060
So I'm going to end
there for a minute.

00:39:15.060 --> 00:39:17.370
And I know I've given
you a lot of information,

00:39:17.370 --> 00:39:20.090
a lot of stories, a lot
of food for thought.

00:39:20.090 --> 00:39:23.040
But what I'm hoping is
that this has given you

00:39:23.040 --> 00:39:26.120
an understanding of
Rwanda as an example

00:39:26.120 --> 00:39:28.690
for post-conflict
societies writ large.

00:39:28.690 --> 00:39:32.930
And one of my main, core
tenets of my research

00:39:32.930 --> 00:39:37.460
is that we have to go deep,
and we have to go broad.

00:39:37.460 --> 00:39:40.470
So we have to go deep to
understand that each context is

00:39:40.470 --> 00:39:43.920
different, and that Rwanda,
what works in Rwanda, what

00:39:43.920 --> 00:39:48.390
doesn't work in Rwanda, might
be different from another place.

00:39:48.390 --> 00:39:51.040
But at the same time,
there are themes

00:39:51.040 --> 00:39:53.370
that cut across
post-conflict societies

00:39:53.370 --> 00:39:56.194
and can help us rethink
wherever we are.

00:39:56.194 --> 00:39:58.110
And so I want you to
think back about what you

00:39:58.110 --> 00:40:00.810
knew and believed about
post-genocide Rwanda

00:40:00.810 --> 00:40:03.240
or post-conflict
societies writ large,

00:40:03.240 --> 00:40:06.620
and what you've learned that
might complicate or complement

00:40:06.620 --> 00:40:07.550
your initial thoughts.

00:40:07.550 --> 00:40:10.450
This was not meant to be a talk
that will clarify everything

00:40:10.450 --> 00:40:13.520
for you, rather a talk
to get you thinking

00:40:13.520 --> 00:40:16.020
about these issues, about
the range of issues,

00:40:16.020 --> 00:40:18.420
and about how you might
be able to fit in.

00:40:18.420 --> 00:40:24.140
So I want to close with a
quote from one of my idols

00:40:24.140 --> 00:40:26.340
in the world,
Desmond Tutu, which

00:40:26.340 --> 00:40:29.040
is "Do your little bit
of good where you're at.

00:40:29.040 --> 00:40:31.770
It's those little bits
of good put together

00:40:31.770 --> 00:40:33.640
that overwhelm the world."

00:40:33.640 --> 00:40:37.920
And so it's not our
responsibly to do it all,

00:40:37.920 --> 00:40:40.390
but I hope that
today this compels

00:40:40.390 --> 00:40:43.810
you to think about where you fit
into the post-conflict society,

00:40:43.810 --> 00:40:47.100
even if you are sitting at
your office here in Cambridge,

00:40:47.100 --> 00:40:50.039
or even if you travel a
little bit to some places that

00:40:50.039 --> 00:40:51.830
might be considered
post-conflict, to delve

00:40:51.830 --> 00:40:55.160
into their history and look
and think about what you can do

00:40:55.160 --> 00:40:58.400
in that very, very small way,
just as I said, staying up

00:40:58.400 --> 00:41:01.130
at night for five minutes,
WhatsApp conversation

00:41:01.130 --> 00:41:05.450
kept a friend from overdrinking
and kept him waking up

00:41:05.450 --> 00:41:08.400
the next morning and I'm glad
to say he's doing really well.

00:41:08.400 --> 00:41:12.830
What are those things that
you can bring to the table?

00:41:12.830 --> 00:41:15.250
With that, I want
to say thank you.

00:41:15.250 --> 00:41:17.600
I want to say thank you
to the Google office

00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:20.760
at Cambridge, to
everyone who came today.

00:41:20.760 --> 00:41:22.740
I'm happy to take
questions and comments,

00:41:22.740 --> 00:41:25.960
but again, I really hope this
opened your eyes to a subject

00:41:25.960 --> 00:41:29.290
that I really care about, and
that I'm passionate about,

00:41:29.290 --> 00:41:31.650
and that I want to
share with people

00:41:31.650 --> 00:41:36.250
who are hopefully also
interested in these kinds

00:41:36.250 --> 00:41:37.340
of issues.

00:41:37.340 --> 00:41:41.880
So once again, thank you
