00:41:54.002 --> 00:41:57.380
NADAV: Hi, can you
talk a little bit more

00:41:57.380 --> 00:42:01.590
about transitional justice and
in the context of the Rwandan

00:42:01.590 --> 00:42:04.560
Genocide, maybe just
give us more details

00:42:04.560 --> 00:42:09.554
of what happened with tribunals
and the historical facts?

00:42:09.554 --> 00:42:11.010
SAMANTHA LAKIN:
Yeah, absolutely.

00:42:11.010 --> 00:42:15.820
So as I mentioned, I'll give you
the transitional justice 101,

00:42:15.820 --> 00:42:19.790
which we do have a Clark
seminar on transitional justice

00:42:19.790 --> 00:42:20.630
at Clark University.

00:42:20.630 --> 00:42:23.360
I'm actually going to give
it to you in a minute.

00:42:23.360 --> 00:42:25.299
Don't tell any
professor who teaches

00:42:25.299 --> 00:42:26.590
that class that I've done this.

00:42:26.590 --> 00:42:27.700
No, I'm just kidding.

00:42:27.700 --> 00:42:29.590
They're my advisor.

00:42:29.590 --> 00:42:31.930
So basically, transitional
justice, as I mentioned,

00:42:31.930 --> 00:42:34.550
is a type of justice
that accompanies

00:42:34.550 --> 00:42:38.890
states and societies
from conflict to peace.

00:42:38.890 --> 00:42:42.580
It's employed in the case
of extraordinary crimes

00:42:42.580 --> 00:42:46.440
and extraordinary grievances--
mass violence, mass atrocities.

00:42:46.440 --> 00:42:48.300
That doesn't only mean
in number but it also

00:42:48.300 --> 00:42:53.680
means in scale of
participation and of targeting.

00:42:53.680 --> 00:42:57.140
So basically the concept is that
ordinary justice or ordinary

00:42:57.140 --> 00:43:02.110
legal courts cannot really
provide justice for these

00:43:02.110 --> 00:43:04.430
extraordinary crimes
like genocide,

00:43:04.430 --> 00:43:07.560
crimes against humanity,
war crimes etc.

00:43:07.560 --> 00:43:12.970
And so transitional justice has
been this array of mechanisms,

00:43:12.970 --> 00:43:15.850
founded and used by the
international community since

00:43:15.850 --> 00:43:19.240
the 1970s or '80s to address
some of these issues that

00:43:19.240 --> 00:43:22.080
ordinary legal justice
cannot address.

00:43:22.080 --> 00:43:27.430
So in Rwanda, we
see the two forms.

00:43:27.430 --> 00:43:30.350
We see legal justice,
which I said, again,

00:43:30.350 --> 00:43:33.380
focuses mostly on
perpetrators and punishment,

00:43:33.380 --> 00:43:35.330
and what we call
symbolic justice, which

00:43:35.330 --> 00:43:37.320
focuses more on
victims and survivors

00:43:37.320 --> 00:43:39.450
and is more future-looking.

00:43:39.450 --> 00:43:42.090
Both are important
and both must be

00:43:42.090 --> 00:43:45.680
there in a post-conflict
society for transitional justice

00:43:45.680 --> 00:43:47.260
to do its job.

00:43:47.260 --> 00:43:50.620
In Rwanda, we have three
main cases that I'll mention.

00:43:50.620 --> 00:43:54.040
One is the establishment of the
International Criminal Tribunal

00:43:54.040 --> 00:43:57.800
for Rwanda, the ICTR, which
was established by the United

00:43:57.800 --> 00:44:01.780
Nations Security
Council in 1995.

00:44:01.780 --> 00:44:05.390
And this basically
was implemented

00:44:05.390 --> 00:44:09.200
like the International Criminal
Tribunal for former Yugoslavia

00:44:09.200 --> 00:44:13.460
and in the legacy and tradition
of the Nuremberg Tribunals

00:44:13.460 --> 00:44:16.650
after World War II to try
the perpetrators, but not

00:44:16.650 --> 00:44:20.660
only the perpetrators but
the big fish, the ones who

00:44:20.660 --> 00:44:22.860
were the organizers,
the masterminds who

00:44:22.860 --> 00:44:28.010
were instrumental in planning
and carrying out in the 1994

00:44:28.010 --> 00:44:29.320
genocide in Rwanda.

00:44:29.320 --> 00:44:32.880
And so the ICTR, I think, was
in operation for 20 years.

00:44:32.880 --> 00:44:35.140
It closed in 2015.

00:44:35.140 --> 00:44:38.310
I do have statistics on
how many people they tried,

00:44:38.310 --> 00:44:40.570
but it wasn't too, too many.

00:44:40.570 --> 00:44:42.320
And it was also very
difficult, because it

00:44:42.320 --> 00:44:44.520
operates with the
bureaucracy of a tribunal.

00:44:44.520 --> 00:44:45.750
So you have trials.

00:44:45.750 --> 00:44:46.730
You have appeals.

00:44:46.730 --> 00:44:49.210
You have a whole
mechanism dedicated.

00:44:49.210 --> 00:44:51.630
The court was also
in Arusha, Tanzania.

00:44:51.630 --> 00:44:52.660
It was not in Rwanda.

00:44:52.660 --> 00:44:55.320
So there was outreach
about the happenings

00:44:55.320 --> 00:44:57.310
of the court in Arusha.

00:44:57.310 --> 00:45:03.110
There was outreach into Rwanda
but reviews are pretty mixed.

00:45:03.110 --> 00:45:07.120
So it goes for the big
fish and it closed in 2015.

00:45:07.120 --> 00:45:09.266
And there were some
very well-known trials

00:45:09.266 --> 00:45:11.140
that came out of there,
including the Akayesu

00:45:11.140 --> 00:45:16.860
case, which proved that
rape is a form of genocide,

00:45:16.860 --> 00:45:19.260
rape is a systematic
form of genocide.

00:45:19.260 --> 00:45:21.580
And it was the first
person convicted of rape

00:45:21.580 --> 00:45:24.690
during genocide, Akayesu.

00:45:24.690 --> 00:45:26.880
So in addition to
the ICTR, are we

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:30.910
have a form of local justice
called the Gacaca tribunals.

00:45:30.910 --> 00:45:35.530
Now, Gacaca were typically
tribunals employed in Rwanda

00:45:35.530 --> 00:45:38.020
for land disputes, where
people would come together

00:45:38.020 --> 00:45:41.040
and elders or trusted
members of society

00:45:41.040 --> 00:45:43.730
would decide what would
happen in a dispute

00:45:43.730 --> 00:45:49.920
and in 2002, I think, or 2005,
this was re-adopte in Rwanda,

00:45:49.920 --> 00:45:52.600
where there was a local
selection of judges,

00:45:52.600 --> 00:45:54.850
and local individuals
would come together

00:45:54.850 --> 00:45:58.710
in their communities,
literally on the grass.

00:45:58.710 --> 00:46:01.860
Perpetrators would confess
what they had done,

00:46:01.860 --> 00:46:05.710
and survivors would
forgive them or would then

00:46:05.710 --> 00:46:07.480
have more knowledge.

00:46:07.480 --> 00:46:10.090
One thing came out of Gacaca
was where people were buried,

00:46:10.090 --> 00:46:11.840
which was a huge deal.

00:46:11.840 --> 00:46:16.430
And so these Gacaca courts were
localized forms of justice.

00:46:16.430 --> 00:46:19.220
They also have their critiques
in which the judges were not

00:46:19.220 --> 00:46:19.970
trained judges.

00:46:19.970 --> 00:46:21.940
There were no lawyers
or representations.

00:46:21.940 --> 00:46:23.523
So there are questions
of due process,

00:46:23.523 --> 00:46:26.312
but basically the
purpose was that the ICTR

00:46:26.312 --> 00:46:28.520
and the national courts
couldn't try the large number

00:46:28.520 --> 00:46:29.607
of perpetrators.

00:46:29.607 --> 00:46:31.190
The prisons were
overflowing and there

00:46:31.190 --> 00:46:34.260
had to be some practical
form of transitional justice.

00:46:34.260 --> 00:46:36.450
And so the Gacaca courts
were formed in order

00:46:36.450 --> 00:46:39.020
to try the lower
level perpetrators--

00:46:39.020 --> 00:46:41.410
people involved in
property theft, people

00:46:41.410 --> 00:46:45.310
involved in assisted killing
and murder, things like that.

00:46:45.310 --> 00:46:48.710
So those were the Gacaca
courts, which closed in 2012.

00:46:48.710 --> 00:46:50.980
And then we have
this third section,

00:46:50.980 --> 00:46:54.200
which is the symbolic justice,
which are more what I discuss

00:46:54.200 --> 00:46:56.130
and absolutely
more what I study,

00:46:56.130 --> 00:47:00.930
which are memorializations,
commemorations, creation

00:47:00.930 --> 00:47:06.780
of memorial sites, burial,
creation of families,

00:47:06.780 --> 00:47:10.370
artificial families in the
aftermath of the genocide,

00:47:10.370 --> 00:47:12.560
official apologies, security.

00:47:12.560 --> 00:47:15.150
These are all the things I would
put under symbolic justice.

00:47:15.150 --> 00:47:17.740
So that's the range that
transitional justice

00:47:17.740 --> 00:47:20.648
takes specifically in Rwanda.

00:47:20.648 --> 00:47:23.090
AUDIENCE: How do you
think our understanding

00:47:23.090 --> 00:47:25.260
of post-conflict
societies in recovery

00:47:25.260 --> 00:47:28.184
affects how we look
at ongoing conflicts?

00:47:28.184 --> 00:47:29.850
SAMANTHA LAKIN: That's
a great question.

00:47:29.850 --> 00:47:30.670
Thank you so much.

00:47:30.670 --> 00:47:33.460
So I think it's interesting
because I was actually

00:47:33.460 --> 00:47:35.570
speaking to my father
yesterday, who's here.

00:47:35.570 --> 00:47:39.817
And he said, "Haven't
we learned anything?"

00:47:39.817 --> 00:47:41.900
And I think a lot of people
ask that-- "Haven't we

00:47:41.900 --> 00:47:42.740
learned anything?"

00:47:42.740 --> 00:47:46.480
The 20th century is known
as the age of genocide,

00:47:46.480 --> 00:47:48.040
the age of conflict.

00:47:48.040 --> 00:47:53.800
Haven't we learned anything
in how we have seen and viewed

00:47:53.800 --> 00:47:56.071
post-conflict societies and
the challenges they have?

00:47:56.071 --> 00:47:57.320
Don't we want to prevent that?

00:47:57.320 --> 00:47:58.670
And of course we do.

00:47:58.670 --> 00:48:01.480
I think the difficulty,
though, is that there are so

00:48:01.480 --> 00:48:05.760
many factors at play that when
a new conflict arises, what

00:48:05.760 --> 00:48:08.700
worked or didn't work, for
example, in Rwanda in 1994,

00:48:08.700 --> 00:48:12.730
in terms of intervention, may
or may not work in Syria today.

00:48:12.730 --> 00:48:14.030
It may or may not backfire.

00:48:14.030 --> 00:48:18.130
And that's why those local,
specialized analysts are just

00:48:18.130 --> 00:48:21.390
as important as the ones
working at the broad level.

00:48:21.390 --> 00:48:24.580
I think, though,
what's particularly

00:48:24.580 --> 00:48:28.390
important is fact-finding
in post-conflict

00:48:28.390 --> 00:48:30.160
when the conflict has subsided.

00:48:30.160 --> 00:48:33.140
Now, of course, conflict doesn't
end when the fighting ends.

00:48:33.140 --> 00:48:35.330
There's elements of
protracted conflict

00:48:35.330 --> 00:48:40.160
that continue long, long after
a ceasefire agreement is signed

00:48:40.160 --> 00:48:42.790
or fighting physically ends.

00:48:42.790 --> 00:48:45.000
And so I think looking at
the complexities and also

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:47.710
the fact-finding, understanding
what really happened,

00:48:47.710 --> 00:48:49.930
what were the patterns
of violence, what

00:48:49.930 --> 00:48:53.160
were some of the triggers,
and analyzing these things,

00:48:53.160 --> 00:48:55.690
analyzing propaganda
and dehumanization

00:48:55.690 --> 00:49:01.780
tactics, groupthink and group
mentality, masculinities

00:49:01.780 --> 00:49:05.200
and initiation into
masculizing groups,

00:49:05.200 --> 00:49:07.940
economic problems-- all
these factors at play

00:49:07.940 --> 00:49:10.640
help us gain a really good
understanding in hindsight

00:49:10.640 --> 00:49:12.540
of what happened post-conflict.

00:49:12.540 --> 00:49:14.580
How do we now apply
that to what's

00:49:14.580 --> 00:49:19.762
going on in active conflict?

00:49:19.762 --> 00:49:21.720
And I think that's the
million dollar question.

00:49:21.720 --> 00:49:23.303
So I don't have a
great answer for you

00:49:23.303 --> 00:49:25.750
but I do think that
understanding the patterns

00:49:25.750 --> 00:49:27.260
and accurately
understanding what's

00:49:27.260 --> 00:49:31.430
happening in current
conflicts is really important,

00:49:31.430 --> 00:49:34.220
and doing more documentation
as the conflict's going on.

00:49:34.220 --> 00:49:36.270
One very quick
example is Burundi.

00:49:36.270 --> 00:49:38.160
So we have an ongoing
conflict in Burundi,

00:49:38.160 --> 00:49:40.080
the country next to Rwanda.

00:49:40.080 --> 00:49:43.734
And some analysts from the
State Department and elsewhere

00:49:43.734 --> 00:49:45.150
are basically
trying to figure out

00:49:45.150 --> 00:49:47.090
what's happening
on the ground now

00:49:47.090 --> 00:49:50.540
and to correctly identify
what kind of violence this is

00:49:50.540 --> 00:49:52.390
and what factors are happening.

00:49:52.390 --> 00:49:54.580
So that when they
are deciding how

00:49:54.580 --> 00:49:57.130
to intervene, which has been
taking a long time but I'm

00:49:57.130 --> 00:50:00.880
hoping will happen
soon, when UN and others

00:50:00.880 --> 00:50:03.940
Western states and other
African states and AU

00:50:03.940 --> 00:50:06.690
are deciding what to do, if
they correctly, more or less,

00:50:06.690 --> 00:50:09.020
identify the elements
of the problem,

00:50:09.020 --> 00:50:10.760
they can create
better solutions.

00:50:10.760 --> 00:50:12.259
And so that's where
I'm hoping we're

00:50:12.259 --> 00:50:16.030
going, which is being able to
disaggregate and then build it

00:50:16.030 --> 00:50:18.420
back, disaggregate into
themes and build it back up

00:50:18.420 --> 00:50:19.000
to prevent.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:21.680
But unfortunately, what
works in one place might not

00:50:21.680 --> 00:50:22.550
work in other place.

00:50:22.550 --> 00:50:23.633
And we've seen that a lot.

00:50:23.633 --> 00:50:25.480
So I'm not trying
to be pessimistic.

00:50:25.480 --> 00:50:29.750
I'm just trying to say
that it's a lot of work

00:50:29.750 --> 00:50:32.992
and we have to do it well.

00:50:32.992 --> 00:50:34.450
AUDIENCE: I like
your presentation.

00:50:37.750 --> 00:50:43.970
As a north Rwandan who
went deep into the subject,

00:50:43.970 --> 00:50:46.660
not only you read the
books like any other person

00:50:46.660 --> 00:50:52.220
could read the book
but you made an impact

00:50:52.220 --> 00:50:57.260
and will make an impact
because we have met those

00:50:57.260 --> 00:51:02.501
you have shown us who were
victimized during the genocide.

00:51:06.050 --> 00:51:10.040
In your experience,
it's really sad

00:51:10.040 --> 00:51:15.100
to get to the point of
justice, as you have explained,

00:51:15.100 --> 00:51:18.320
transitional and
the other phases,

00:51:18.320 --> 00:51:23.730
three phases, what do you think
of bringing in justice when

00:51:23.730 --> 00:51:27.560
we hear, the whole
world, hear people

00:51:27.560 --> 00:51:31.830
who deny the existence
of this genocide?

00:51:31.830 --> 00:51:36.160
And mostly, let's say we live
here in the United States

00:51:36.160 --> 00:51:40.280
and elsewhere in Europe,
some of the perpetrators

00:51:40.280 --> 00:51:44.220
have fled the country and
they are all over the world.

00:51:44.220 --> 00:51:48.280
And they have come
about this denial

00:51:48.280 --> 00:51:51.410
that the genocide
has not taken place.

00:51:51.410 --> 00:51:56.070
Others will come
to say, "Well, we

00:51:56.070 --> 00:51:59.710
accept that the genocide
has taken place,

00:51:59.710 --> 00:52:03.390
but there was a
double genocide."

00:52:03.390 --> 00:52:05.915
Another group will come
and say, well, this

00:52:05.915 --> 00:52:09.520
is a group of the
deniers of genocide

00:52:09.520 --> 00:52:12.590
yet they're not Rwandans.

00:52:12.590 --> 00:52:15.300
They're not a group of
Rwandan perpetrators,

00:52:15.300 --> 00:52:18.010
and they have not been
even in the country.

00:52:18.010 --> 00:52:21.990
They go ahead and if I could
use the world "preach" here

00:52:21.990 --> 00:52:24.715
and tehre about
that kind of denial.

00:52:27.410 --> 00:52:34.170
How will you bring that
into being or bringing

00:52:34.170 --> 00:52:37.370
a sort of justice to
these kinds of stories

00:52:37.370 --> 00:52:40.290
around the denial of justice?

00:52:40.290 --> 00:52:40.810
Thank you.

00:52:40.810 --> 00:52:42.920
SAMANTHA LAKIN: Thank
you, Professor Bayingana.

00:52:42.920 --> 00:52:45.130
Professor Bayingana brings
up a really great point,

00:52:45.130 --> 00:52:47.880
which is what forms
does denial take

00:52:47.880 --> 00:52:49.820
and what do we do about it?

00:52:49.820 --> 00:52:50.692
Denial is a problem.

00:52:50.692 --> 00:52:51.650
And it's not a new one.

00:52:51.650 --> 00:52:53.280
We've seen it with Armenia.

00:52:53.280 --> 00:52:55.110
We've seen it after
the Holocaust.

00:52:55.110 --> 00:52:57.470
After almost every
major conflict,

00:52:57.470 --> 00:53:00.172
we have people who
for some reason,

00:53:00.172 --> 00:53:01.630
whether it's
political or personal,

00:53:01.630 --> 00:53:06.760
cannot handle the truth of
what happened and try to give

00:53:06.760 --> 00:53:07.960
another example.

00:53:07.960 --> 00:53:11.030
So one way this happens
is by completely denying.

00:53:11.030 --> 00:53:13.040
One way is by
manipulating the facts

00:53:13.040 --> 00:53:16.030
and saying it was not a
genocide, it was a civil war.

00:53:16.030 --> 00:53:21.160
Or, yes, Tutsi were killed in
1994 but also there were crimes

00:53:21.160 --> 00:53:29.450
against Hutu in 1995, "96, '97.

00:53:29.450 --> 00:53:31.860
That concept of double
genocide, that it was not only

00:53:31.860 --> 00:53:35.040
Tutsi who were killed but after
that Hutu were killed as they

00:53:35.040 --> 00:53:37.816
were exiting the country
and were targeted,

00:53:37.816 --> 00:53:40.350
that's the theory
of double genocide.

00:53:40.350 --> 00:53:42.590
And to that I would
say two things

00:53:42.590 --> 00:53:44.420
about dealing with deniers.

00:53:44.420 --> 00:53:47.110
One way we can deal with
deniers is to ignore them,

00:53:47.110 --> 00:53:49.640
is not to give them
a platform to speak.

00:53:49.640 --> 00:53:51.940
Because when deniers are
interviewed on television

00:53:51.940 --> 00:53:56.420
or they have a chance
to write in media.

00:53:56.420 --> 00:53:57.920
And of course,
there is free speech

00:53:57.920 --> 00:53:59.295
in these countries
you mentioned.

00:53:59.295 --> 00:54:01.100
People can publish
anywhere they want.

00:54:01.100 --> 00:54:04.160
But if they're known denialists,
and if they are causing harm

00:54:04.160 --> 00:54:07.992
to people, there are ways is
to choose someone else, someone

00:54:07.992 --> 00:54:09.700
who maybe has a more
balanced perspective

00:54:09.700 --> 00:54:14.100
and is not considered an
outright denialist when

00:54:14.100 --> 00:54:17.830
any news outlet
interviews people.

00:54:17.830 --> 00:54:21.100
One survivor told me that denial
feels like the genocide is

00:54:21.100 --> 00:54:22.580
happening over again.

00:54:22.580 --> 00:54:24.560
Because basically
their family were

00:54:24.560 --> 00:54:26.369
killed during the genocide.

00:54:26.369 --> 00:54:27.910
And then when someone
denies it, they

00:54:27.910 --> 00:54:31.290
deny your right
of acknowledgment.

00:54:31.290 --> 00:54:32.810
They deny your right to grieve.

00:54:32.810 --> 00:54:35.790
They deny your right to
feel how you want to feel.

00:54:35.790 --> 00:54:38.417
They deny what happened to
you, and they're harming

00:54:38.417 --> 00:54:40.500
your ability to move forward
because you cannot be

00:54:40.500 --> 00:54:41.050
recognized.

00:54:41.050 --> 00:54:42.800
And we see this kind
of in-limbo situation

00:54:42.800 --> 00:54:44.880
in Armenia, where
people are very

00:54:44.880 --> 00:54:48.130
hurt because their
situation and their reality

00:54:48.130 --> 00:54:49.800
is not being recognized.

00:54:49.800 --> 00:54:54.310
And so I think besides
this is ignoring and not

00:54:54.310 --> 00:54:56.030
engaging, because
denialists will keep,

00:54:56.030 --> 00:54:57.940
as you said,
preaching, regardless

00:54:57.940 --> 00:55:00.510
of what factual evidence comes.

00:55:00.510 --> 00:55:05.050
I think the second point is
this categorization that's

00:55:05.050 --> 00:55:05.940
really helpful.

00:55:05.940 --> 00:55:09.540
I think the legal crime category
is genocide, war crimes, crimes

00:55:09.540 --> 00:55:11.860
against humanity,
and all that has

00:55:11.860 --> 00:55:18.110
been put into developing these
very thorough categories is

00:55:18.110 --> 00:55:19.000
helpful.

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:22.690
So when the UN deemed that
Rwanda was a genocide,

00:55:22.690 --> 00:55:25.980
there are facts and evidence in
terms of fact-finding missions,

00:55:25.980 --> 00:55:28.340
in terms of intent,
intent to destroy

00:55:28.340 --> 00:55:31.100
a group in whole or in part,
intent to destroy the Tutsi

00:55:31.100 --> 00:55:32.790
people.

00:55:32.790 --> 00:55:35.750
These were present and
proven in the case of Rwanda.

00:55:35.750 --> 00:55:38.360
And so it is a
genocide, according

00:55:38.360 --> 00:55:41.490
to international legal order,
if that's what you respect.

00:55:41.490 --> 00:55:44.180
And most people, I
think most countries do.

00:55:44.180 --> 00:55:46.360
And so sticking to
those definitions

00:55:46.360 --> 00:55:48.560
and the facts is where
you can't go wrong.

00:55:48.560 --> 00:55:52.200
At a certain point, if you
start getting into the emotion

00:55:52.200 --> 00:55:55.050
and trying to convince
people, it can get very messy,

00:55:55.050 --> 00:55:58.170
but the facts of the matter
are the ones that stick there.

00:55:58.170 --> 00:56:00.460
And the ones that are
grounded in international law,

00:56:00.460 --> 00:56:03.170
international theory,
that's where I think we

00:56:03.170 --> 00:56:07.870
can really keep continuing
with helping to fight denial.

00:56:07.870 --> 00:56:10.970
But denial is very
harmful for everyone,

00:56:10.970 --> 00:56:12.970
and it's a big, big issue
in Rwanda right now.

00:56:12.970 --> 00:56:15.820
So thank you so much.

00:56:15.820 --> 00:56:17.920
Thank you, everyone.

